            <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://elecming.com/post/20250213t191758--how-i-manage-documents-if-all-of-them-in-one-flat-folder-using-calibredbel__emacs_technology/" />
            <id>https://elecming.com/post/20250213t191758--how-i-manage-documents-if-all-of-them-in-one-flat-folder-using-calibredbel__emacs_technology/</id>
            <updated>2025-02-15T01:30:24&#43;09:00</updated>
            <published>2025-02-13T19:17:00&#43;09:00</published>
            <author>
                    <name>Damon Chan</name>
                    <uri>https://elecming.com/</uri>
                    <email>elecming@gmail.com</email>
                    </author>
            <rights>[CC BY-NC-SA 4.0](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/deed.en)</rights><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;You may not know: there is one type of metadata in Calibre, called folder metadata. It is also be used in elink device if you use calibre to transfer files to elink device. A hidden file named &lt;code&gt;.metadata.calibre&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unlike the original database &lt;code&gt;metadata.db&lt;/code&gt;, metadata needs ebooks be resided inside a non-flat folder, while the &lt;code&gt;.metadata.calibre&lt;/code&gt; is a json file, and it has all the metadata for all documents/ebooks under one flat folder.&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
            
            
            
            
            
                
                    
                
                    
                        
                            
                            
                            
